{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518769"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:07:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:07:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12946"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12946"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.12,0.1,0.08,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90637"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5384"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74840"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31101"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90637"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man presents to the hospital with a two-week history of right upper quadrant abdominal pain, anorexia, and jaundice. He admits to drinking about 8-10 beers daily for the past 15 years. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears ill. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 100/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37\u00b0C. He is jaundiced and has mild tenderness in his right upper abdomen with hepatomegaly. Investigations reveal: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 180 U/L (10-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 70 U/L (7-56)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 88 \u00b5mol/L (2-24)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHBsAg: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBc: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBs: positive\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltrasound: hepatomegaly and fatty infiltration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intensive nutritional support","Corticosteroid therapy","Liver transplantation evaluation","N-acetylcysteine infusion","Abstinence counselling only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and biochemical features consistent with alcoholic hepatitis, characterised by jaundice, right upper quadrant pain, and a pattern of liver enzyme elevation with AST greater than ALT (typically in a 2:1 ratio). The history of significant alcohol consumption supports this diagnosis. The hepatitis B serology (negative HBsAg and anti-HBc with positive anti-HBs) indicates immunity from past vaccination rather than current or previous infection, ruling out viral hepatitis as a cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntensive nutritional support\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management for alcoholic hepatitis. Patients with alcoholic hepatitis are often malnourished, and high-calorie protein diets have been associated with improved six-month survival compared to low daily calorie intake. Nutritional support should be initiated promptly while other assessments are ongoing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroid therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be beneficial in severe alcoholic hepatitis, particularly when Maddrey\u0027s discriminant function score is \u0026gt;32 or hepatic encephalopathy is present. Maddrey\u0027s discriminant function is calculated as [4.6 \u00d7 (patient\u0027s prothrombin time - control prothrombin time in seconds)] + serum bilirubin in mg/dL, and is used to assess the severity of alcoholic hepatitis. However, corticosteroids should only be considered after several days of supportive care, including nutritional support, and after completing a septic screen. Steroids are associated with an increased risk of infection and should not be given if infection is present or suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver transplantation evaluation\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration for patients with severe, life-threatening alcoholic hepatitis not responding to other treatments. However, most transplant centres require a period of abstinence (typically six months) before considering transplantation for alcohol-related liver disease. It is not an immediate management step in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used as an antidote for paracetamol overdose and may have some benefit in non-paracetamol acute liver failure. However, there is limited evidence supporting its routine use in alcoholic hepatitis, and it would not be considered first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbstinence counselling only\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient as a standalone treatment for alcoholic hepatitis. While abstinence from alcohol is crucial for long-term management and should be addressed, this patient requires active medical management for his acute condition. Abstinence counselling should be part of a comprehensive treatment plan that includes nutritional support and other appropriate interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intensive nutritional support is the first-line management for alcoholic hepatitis, associated with improved six-month survival.","Corticosteroids should only be considered after nutritional support and septic screening in severe alcoholic hepatitis.","Maddrey\u0027s discriminant function score \u003E32 or presence of hepatic encephalopathy are indicators for considering corticosteroid therapy in patients with alcoholic hepatitis."],"references":["Shah NJ, Royer A, John S. Alcoholic Hepatitis. In: StatPearls [online]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing. [Updated 2023 Jan 2]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470217/","Why do we use steroids, Maddrey\u0027s Discriminant Function, and the Lille score in Alcohol-Associated Hepatitis? In: American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases [online]. 2022 Jan 9 [cited on 2024 Feb 27]. Available at: https://www.aasld.org/liver-fellow-network/core-series/why-series/why-do-we-use-steroids-maddreys-discriminant-function"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74840"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12946"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74840"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T13:43:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T13:44:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5384"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90637"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","